Doesn't really matter.

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:26.840
This is my input data.

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:32.799
And then, again, I'm constructing my model, and now you will see the same principles like

00:10:32.799 --> 00:10:33.799
before.

00:10:33.799 --> 00:10:36.679
I have my encoder model, which is a standalone model.

00:10:36.679 --> 00:10:37.919
I can define like that.

00:10:37.919 --> 00:10:41.200
The decoder model, I can define like that.

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:47.679
And now with the variation autoencoders, the action really is in the loss function, because

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:49.960
on the one hand, I want to reconstruct the input.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:54.520
On the other hand, I have a regularization term, which is different between different

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:56.640
types of autoencoders.

00:10:56.640 --> 00:11:00.520
Here I have one specific loss can be a different one.

00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:07.679
But still, this ends up being like five lines of code or so, and I'm all set up.

00:11:07.679 --> 00:11:13.280
And after I've set it up like that, again, I'm just doing the same kind of iteration

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:15.900
over the code.

