gonna end up all the same always.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:28.159
And now let's see the snowflakes.

00:11:28.239 --> 00:11:34.039
So I have here, they don't look much worse than the input, actually.

00:11:34.039 --> 00:11:35.039
Yeah.

00:11:35.039 --> 00:11:36.039
Okay.

00:11:36.039 --> 00:11:45.520
So these were examples of models which are quite hard to code if you're using static execution,

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:47.919
as we have been doing until now.

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:52.719
But this gets a lot easier with eager execution.

00:11:52.719 --> 00:11:54.919
But there's more to it.

00:11:54.919 --> 00:11:58.239
More stuff, but important stuff when doing the coding.

00:11:58.239 --> 00:12:04.880
For example, what's really hard is to see what's going on in deep learning.

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:10.679
If I think of GitHub issues we tend to get, what may happen is, like, people want to code

00:12:10.679 --> 00:12:13.760
their own loss function or their own metric.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:16.239
You can do that in Keras, okay.

00:12:16.239 --> 00:12:18.799
But then you get a shape error somewhere in there.

00:12:18.799 --> 00:12:21.640
So the shapes don't match, can happen.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:28.440
Right now, people tend to get stuck because they just don't know how to debug this.

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:33.000
And with eager execution, what you can do is you can just print it out.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.039
Like printf debugging.

00:12:35.039 --> 00:12:38.440
So it's, I mean, you're gonna remove it later, right?

00:12:38.440 --> 00:12:41.080
So why not do it?

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:42.080
That's one thing.

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:47.799
Another thing is you can have more modular code, because you can isolate logic in small

00:12:47.799 --> 00:12:49.479
custom models.

00:12:49.479 --> 00:12:55.640
And then also, when sometimes we are getting, we want to have architectures where you can't

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:58.559
just chain the layers one after each other.

00:12:58.559 --> 00:13:02.000
You need some interleaving of logic.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:03.520
I'm gonna show that.

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:09.880
So these are three examples for how eager execution makes things easier, actually.

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:12.039
Now easy debugging, for example.

00:13:12.039 --> 00:13:17.239
Here you have this loop again where I'm doing the recording of the actions.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:23.000
And I'm gonna calculate the loss and then doing the back prop.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:28.479
And now really what happens when you actually code this, in practice, you're quite often

00:13:28.479 --> 00:13:33.119
you may get shape not matching shapes in deep learning.

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:37.719
And then what I can do here is I can just really print it out.

00:13:37.719 --> 00:13:40.200
And I cannot just print out the shape.

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:42.880
I can print out the actual images.

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:51.679
So when I do this print generated images, I really see, like, float tensors, yeah?

00:13:51.679 --> 00:13:55.900
Like a 4D array of floats.

00:13:55.900 --> 00:14:00.960
And this is, like, invaluable for debugging, actually, when you're writing that code.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:02.080
Also here with the gradients.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:06.520
So one thing if your network just doesn't train, yeah?

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:12.640
One thing that can happen is that the gradients just vanish or get too big, for example.

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:16.200
And so what I can just do, I can print them out.

00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:19.559
And there I have it.

00:14:19.559 --> 00:14:22.200
Another thing, modular code.

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:29.719
So what we often see in longer deep learning examples is, like, I have lots of layers.

00:14:29.719 --> 00:14:31.479
For example, the ConvNet.

00:14:31.479 --> 00:14:34.880
And all these convolutional layers, they want their parameters specified.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:39.520
And so it gets long and lots of duplicated stuff.

00:14:39.520 --> 00:14:46.640
And here what I can do, I can just take part of the logic and put it in a custom model

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:47.960
for itself.

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:51.880
Here what we often do is either upsampling or downsampling.

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:54.840
So convolution or deconvolution.

00:14:54.840 --> 00:15:00.760
And a typical, for example, downsampling module could look like a Conv layer and some batch

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:03.359
normalization and dropout, yeah?

00:15:03.359 --> 00:15:08.119
And perhaps another Conv layer, another batch normalization, another dropout.

00:15:08.119 --> 00:15:11.760
And now I don't have to type that again and again and again.

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:17.679
I can just define it as an own submodule, so to say.

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:22.760
And then I can go on and use that.

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:27.919
If I go back to my generator, this was from the variational autoencoder.

00:15:27.919 --> 00:15:34.239
This does a bunch of downsamplings and a bunch of upsamplings again.

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:40.559
And here I use my custom module, which I defined on the previous slide.

00:15:40.559 --> 00:15:45.359
So code gets a lot more readable like that, too.

00:15:45.359 --> 00:15:54.919
And then, yeah, a nice example for this interleaving logic is, so like one or two years ago, actually

00:15:54.919 --> 00:16:04.200
since 2013, so a bit longer, a mechanism was described where we have in a network, where

00:16:05.159 --> 00:16:08.599
the network learns where to direct its attention.

00:16:08.599 --> 00:16:14.919
So let's say I have this task of describing image captions or learning image captions.

00:16:14.919 --> 00:16:21.640
So the network is shown pictures and is asked to generate a description for it.

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:27.039
Like the bird flies over the lake or something, yeah?

00:16:27.039 --> 00:16:34.880
And the architecture is I have a convent to extract the features, yeah?

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:36.559
Normal image processing.

00:16:36.559 --> 00:16:41.840
And then I have an RNN, which is supposed to generate the caption.

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:48.520
And now the idea is that as the RNN goes on generating this caption, so one word after

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:55.960
another, another place in the image is important, right?

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:59.239
Like first it's the bird and then it's the lake.

00:16:59.239 --> 00:17:06.040
So the network shifts its attention from around different locations in the image.

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:12.719
And this really you can code in static TensorFlow, but you can't code in straightforward Keras.

00:17:12.719 --> 00:17:16.400
So and it gets a bit nasty in TensorFlow.

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:23.000
But now with eager execution, what you can just do is you have your decoder, which is

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:27.160
the RNN, which is going to generate that sentence.

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:35.199
And as this RNN generates every word, it's going to call the attention module to direct

00:17:35.199 --> 00:17:37.079
its attention.

00:17:37.079 --> 00:17:44.239
Things like that have really been really difficult to do without that.

00:17:44.239 --> 00:17:45.599
And now, okay.

00:17:45.599 --> 00:17:46.599
First documentation.

00:17:46.599 --> 00:17:50.439
So we already have lots of examples for that on the blog.

00:17:50.439 --> 00:17:58.359
So these are all links to blog articles using eager execution for things like image-to-image

00:17:58.359 --> 00:18:04.680
translation, image captioning, newer style transfer, and newer machine translation.

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:12.599
And of course, we also have documentation how to construct an eager execution model.

